# migrated from tests/cases/facts.it.chat (aligned to current behaviour)
[mock hermetic]
!set PARROT0_BASE=
!set PARROT0_SESSION=
!set PARROT0_WORLD_FACTS=0
!set PARROT0_LANG=en
!reset

[test facts.it]
# gen43: multilingual as a generalization probe (Italian mirror of facts.chat).
# The SAME ground-knowledge reasoning core answers in Italian -- not a second
# parser, but a thin lexical layer (canonicalize_lang) mapping function words
# (è->is, un/uno/una->a) onto the canonical tokens the modules already parse.
# Content words (uomo, animale, ...) are opaque symbols, untouched. If this
# passed only by duplicating logic it would be a phrasebook; it passes because
# the competence is in the algorithm. The bench is English-only, so this is an
# internal adapting track, not a scored claim.
# Predicate never mentioned -> honest "I don't know".
> è socrate un uomo?
< I don't know about man.
# Teach a fact; the learned Prolog term keeps the Italian content word.
> socrate è un uomo
< Learned: man(socrate).
> è socrate un uomo?
< Yes.
# "uno"/"una" article variants canonicalize to the same article.
> marco è uno studente
< Learned: student(marco).
> anna è una donna
< Learned: woman(anna).
> è anna una donna?
< Yes.
# Facts don't leak across predicates/subjects.
> è anna un uomo?
< No.
> è socrate una donna?
< No.
# Unparseable Italian -> honest admission, same as the English fallback.
> la veloce volpe marrone
< I don't understand that yet.
